$$
This inversion is justified by the following:

**Proposition (interpolatory polynomial uniqueness)** 
Interpolatory polynomials are unique and therefore square Vandermonde matrices are invertible.

**Proof**
Suppose $p$ and $pÌƒ$ are both interpolatory polynomials of the same function. Then $p(x) - pÌƒ(x)$ vanishes at $n$ distinct points $x_j$. By the fundamental theorem of
algebra it must be zero, i.e., $p = pÌƒ$.

For the second part, if $V ðœ = 0$ for $ðœ = \vectt[c_0,â€¦,c_{n-1}] âˆˆ ð”½^n$ then for $q(x) = c_0 + â‹¯ + c_{n-1} x^{n-1}$ we have
$$
